Since \emph{M} is a linear transformation,

\begin{align*}M\begin{bmatrix}1\\ 0\end{bmatrix} = M\begin{bmatrix}2\\ 1\end{bmatrix} - M\begin{bmatrix}1\\ 1\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}0\\ 1\end{bmatrix} - \begin{bmatrix}1\\ 0\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}-1\\ 1\end{bmatrix}\end{align*}

and

\begin{align*}M\begin{bmatrix}0\\ 1\end{bmatrix} = 2M\begin{bmatrix}1\\ 1\end{bmatrix} - M\begin{bmatrix}2\\ 1\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}2\\ 0\end{bmatrix} - \begin{bmatrix}0\\ 1\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}2\\ -1\end{bmatrix}\end{align*}

Hence

\begin{align*}M = \begin{bmatrix}-1 & 2\\ 1 & -1\end{bmatrix}\end{align*}

hints:
Remember the formula for the inverse of a 2-x-2 matrix:

\begin{align*}A = \begin{bmatrix} a & b \\ c & d \end{bmatrix}
\quad \rightarrow \quad
A^{-1} = \left(\frac{1}{ad - bc}\right)\begin{bmatrix} d & -b \\ -c & a \end{bmatrix}\end{align*}
provided $ad - bc \ne 0$.
